00:28:41,740 --> 00:28:43,740
well, then it just isn't there.

675
00:28:43,740 --> 00:28:45,740
Over here,

676
00:28:45,740 --> 00:28:47,740
there's another term,

677
00:28:47,740 --> 00:28:49,740
and it's the electric current.

678
00:28:49,740 --> 00:28:51,740
It's called J,

679
00:28:51,740 --> 00:28:53,740
and I'll define it for you later.

680
00:28:53,740 --> 00:28:55,740
But for the moment,

681
00:28:55,740 --> 00:28:57,740
I want to study the Maxwell equations

682
00:28:57,740 --> 00:28:59,740
without electric current and charges.

683
00:28:59,740 --> 00:29:01,740
We want to see if we can understand

684
00:29:01,740 --> 00:29:03,740
why those equations

685
00:29:03,740 --> 00:29:05,740
are the same in every reference frame.

686
00:29:05,740 --> 00:29:07,740
How can that possibly be?

687
00:29:07,740 --> 00:29:09,740
Why is it a puzzle?

688
00:29:09,740 --> 00:29:11,740
It's a puzzle because,

689
00:29:11,740 --> 00:29:13,740
as we're going to see,

690
00:29:13,740 --> 00:29:15,740
these equations describe light waves

691
00:29:15,740 --> 00:29:17,740
moving always with the same speed.

692
00:29:17,740 --> 00:29:19,740
They're always moving at the same speed.

693
00:29:19,740 --> 00:29:21,740
They're always moving at the same speed.

694
00:29:21,740 --> 00:29:23,740
They always move with the same speed,

695
00:29:23,740 --> 00:29:25,740
the speed of light.

696
00:29:25,740 --> 00:29:27,740
They move down the axis with the speed of light.

697
00:29:27,740 --> 00:29:29,740
How can they possibly be the same

698
00:29:29,740 --> 00:29:31,740
in every reference frame?

699
00:29:31,740 --> 00:29:33,740
After all, if I was a reference frame

